mboy, New Jersey.\nJ, \u03a1 KOYEN,\nCarpenter and Builder\nHat 1 mates Furnished,\nJobbing Attended To.\n883 Stale St., Perth Amboy. Tel. 314-J\nHANS A. DINNE6E.\u00ce\n'ainter.\n85 North First St.\nThe Fred Christiansen\nConstruction Company,\n<arprntern nod Rnllder*.\nOffice tutd shop, 224-220 .Madison Av,\nPerth Amboy\u00b7 Estimates cheerfully\nfurnished. Jobbing promptly attended\nto. L\u00b7. D. Phone, 814.\nHENRY NELSON.\n('arpentera and lluUdera.\nIH-' !>lafll\u00bboa Ave.\nNielsen Ronager\nCarpenters and Builders,\nEstimates Furnished.\nJobbing Promptly Attended to.\n170 Fayette St., Cor. Maple.\nPerth Aniboy, \u039d J.\nMarins TH. PEDERSON,\nMason Contractor,\nLaurie St. Cor. Woodbridge Road.\nJ\u00cbNS M. SORENSEN\nPainter and Paperhanger,\n108 Barclay St.,\nPerth Amboy.\nE. O. CARLSON,\nPaintee. and l'aperhunger\nLatest Designs\nIn Wall Paper.\n\u0399\u03b2\u03b4 Market St., Perth Amboy, N. J.\nWhile watching t\u00f9u particular\nclassification that appeals to you, do\nnot overlook all thu other want ads.\nbusiness are the rule. And \"read\njustments\" usually mean \"opportuni\nties\" for worker\u00bb\u2014chance to secure\nIhe \"better\" jobs. Want advertisers\nunderstand these matters\u00bb\nNOT SMITH'S\nFIRST TIME\nThe New Jersey D\u00e9mocratie\nLeaJer Has Been Opposed to\nBryan Before.\nCOOLNESS AT WHITE HOUSE\nWashington, D. C., May 2:\u2014Re\nferring to the recent democratic state\nconvention a local paper prints the\nfollowing editorial:\n\"Former Senator James Smith, of\nNew Jersey, who goes to Denver as\nan anti-Bryan delegate, should serve\non the platform committee of the\nconvention. He was one of Mr. Gor\nman's lieutenants In amending the\nWilson tariff bill In the Senate, by\nwhich the measure was made to take\non larger degrees of proteotlon, and\nprobably still retains his protection\nviews. This, therefore, Is not the\nfirst time that Mr. Smith lias been\nIn antagonism to Mr. Bryan, who at\nthat time was a champion of tha Wil\nson bill. The tariff Is to figure prom\ninently at Denver, and with the Bry\nanltes pulling in one direction and\nthe men of the Smith stamp In an\nother the reeult may not et this time\nbe forecast.\"\nThat there Is a coolness between\nthe President and some of the lead\ners on the republican side of the\nHouse is well known. It Is largely\ndue to the fact that Mr. Roosevelt\nliaa been somewhat Insistent with\nreference to the legislation he want\ned passed by the present congress.\nIt Is asserted in some quarters thlat\nthe President has not been as tact\nful in handling some of the Con\ngressmen as was the late President\nMcKinley, and there seems to be\ngood grounds for such an Idea. Fears\nare entertained, however, that not\nonly will some good legislation be\nneglected as a result of the failure\n4-1\u03bb a 4-i \u00abr a \u0397\u03bb\u03bb \u0399\u03b1\u03b7-lalntlvA\ndepartments to agree thoroughly, but\nthat tile next House may have a\ndemocratic majority as a result of\nthe difference In opinion.\nH. C. Tansey, of Newark, a prom\ninent business man of Essex county,\nwho is spending a few toys in this\ncity, does not believe in the theory of\ncoropral punishment for ohlldren. In\ndiscussing the matter he said: ''Since\nI have become a student of the\nwhims, peculiarity and temperament\nof children I have been able to dis\ncover the difference in results in\nfamilies where corporal punishment\nwas employed and where not em\nployed. The child who has been\nreared by the plan of moral suasion\nmakes a better amn or woman than\nthe one given the heroic treatment\nwith the rod.\"\n0. S. A.\nCANDIDATES AT\nA CONFERENCE\nWASHINGTON, D. 0., May 2:\nThe conference of governors nnd\nother publio men which the Presi\ndent has called for a three days'\nsession beginning May\" 12, is going\nto be an Important gathering. In\nthe first place, ever? presidential\ncandidate will be on hand\u2014Taft,\nBryan, Hughes, Johnson, Fairbanks,\nGray, Cannon, Knox and all the rest.\nGoyernor Freer, of Hawaii, will\nmake the pilgrimage from Honolulu\nwith three delegates; the governor\nof Alaska has sent an enthusiastic\nacceptance, and then there's a host\nof plain American citUens who will\nattend as delegates from all the na\ntional organizatlops which have to\ndo with the conservation of the\ncountry'\u00bb natural resources.\nForests, rivers, soils, mining,\ntransportation and agrionlture are\nsoma of the big subjects that will be\ndiscussed. President Roosevelt has\nlong been deeply interested in the\nproblem of how to get the most out\nof the earth while yet leaving the\ngreatest possible store for future\ngenerations. The alarming In\ncrease in the devastation of a num\nber of our natural resources, the\nwasteful cutting of timber, erosion\nof soil, river-floods, etc., have\nbrought him to believe that there\nshould be some concerted action all\nover the country looking to their\nmore conservative use and better\nprotoction. Therefore, he has sum\nmoned the governors of the states\nto meet with him and, with the help\nof a large number of other publio\nmen, scientists, engineers and econ\nomists, try to thresh out a future\ncourse of action which shall result\nIn a policy whereby it w i llbepooth\nin a policy whereby it will be pos\nsible to eat the cake and still have\nsome of it left.\nIf you are, and want a building\nthat will stand a thousand years,\nInvestigate the merits of\nCEMENT STONE\n10 \"er csnt* Cheaper than Brick\nTWICE \u03948 DURABLE.\nMakes a Better Looking Building,\nWe manufacture everything neo\nessary for a budding from th\u00b7\nsewer to the roof.\nPerth Amboy Cement\nStone Roofing Tile Co.\nWorks: GHFbrd and Chapman Ave.\nAddress: Cor. State Paterson St\nWe are prepared to accept\nFurS Simp\nsubject to full Insurance against dam\nago by Are, moths, etc., and against\nloss by burglarly.\nAlterations, lf'desired, at extreme\nly moderate prices.\nAll furs extensively repaired will\nbe storey free of charge. Furs called\nfor